<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>HSBC PLANS 50,000 JOB CUTS IN GLOBAL RESTRUCTURING</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> HSBC said Tuesday that it would cut as many as 50,000 jobs around the world and try to reduce costs by as much as $5 billion a year by 2017 as it laid out its plans to restructure its global businesses, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/10/business/dealbook/hsbc-job-cuts-axe-25000-50000-saving-drive.html"> Chad Bray reports in DealBook</a>. About 25,000 jobs will be lost through the sale of the bankâs businesses in Turkey and Brazil, and an additional 20,000 to 25,000 jobs will be eliminated as part of the restructuring. However, the bank is <b> increasingly focusing on Asia</b>, saying that it would expand its asset management and insurance operations in hopes of capturing âexpected opportunities from emerging wealth in the region.â The bank also plans to increase its <b>business in the Pearl River Delta</b> in the southern Chinese province of Guangdong and in parts of Southeast Asia. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In April, HSBC, which generates more than half of its earnings from Asia, said it was reviewing whether to move its headquarters from Britain, where a bank tax has hit lenders particularly hard. On Tuesday, the bank said it would <b>complete the review by the end of the year</b>. In the meantime, HSBC said it would begin <b>setting up a âring-fenced bankâ in Britain </b> as required by regulators. The country is giving banks until 2019 to shield their retail banking operations from the effects of investment banking and other activities in the event of another financial crisis â a process known as ring fencing. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">HSBC also said it would reduce so-called risk-weighted assets, a measure of the risk of the capital it holds, by 25 percent, or about $290 billion. About half of those reductions will <b>come from the investment banking business</b>, the lender said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Investors appeared to be underwhelmed by the bankâs plans. HSBC shares edged down in morning trading in London and in afternoon trading in Hong Kong. âThe initiatives taken by management are all welcome,â Sanford C. Bernstein said in a report led by analyst Chirantan Barua in London, Bloomberg News reports. However, the report also said that the bank âhas <b>failed to bring out anything radically different</b> from moves which have been widely expected for some months now.â<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>REGULATOR SAID TO HAVE URGED DEUTSCHE BANK CHIEFSâ EXIT</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> It was well known that shareholders of Deutsche Bank were unhappy with Anshu Jain and JÃ¼rgen Fitschen, who are both stepping down as co-chief executives, but German regulators were also pressuring the bank to change its leadership, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/09/business/dealbook/regulator-said-to-have-pressed-for-exit-of-deutsche-chiefs.html"> Jack Ewing and Peter Eavis write in DealBook</a>. According to two people briefed on the events that contributed to the change in leadership, officials at the German regulator, known as BaFin, were unhappy over the way the two executives had handled an investigation into alleged manipulation of benchmark interest rates by bank employees. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Jain and Mr. Fitschen were not accused of taking part in the manipulation, which occurred while Mr. Jain was head of the Deutsche Bank investment bank. But United States and British authorities complained in public statements that Deutsche Bank had been <b>slow to provide information and had kept incomplete records</b>. In its deferred-prosecution agreement with Deutsche Bank, for instance, the United States Justice Department said that the bank committed ânumerous unintentional but significant mistakes in the preservation, collection, and production of documents, audio, and data,â including the destruction of thousands of hours of audio recordings. Comments like these <b>shook BaFinâs confidence in the bankâs leadership</b>, the two people briefed on BaFinâs actions said. In particular, BaFin is said to have been frustrated by Deutsche Bankâs poor record-keeping. However, Michael Golden, a spokesman for the bank, <b>strongly denied that pressure from regulators was a factor</b> in the executivesâ departure.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>WHAT MERGERS SAY ABOUT U.S. ECONOMY</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Robust deal-making activity is often seen as a barometer of a healthy economy, but in contrast to previous merger booms, the recent flurry of acquisitions in the United States may actually be a sign that businesses are running out of growth options, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/09/business/dealbook/mergers-might-not-signal-optimism.html"> Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column</a>. He cites a Citigroup report that notes that revenue growth at American companies has been declining every year for the last five years and points out that Charter Communications didnât mention revenue projections at all when it announced its $55 billion acquisition of Time Warner Cable, and neither did Avago when it announced its $37 billion takeover of Broadcom. âIndeed, <b>cost-cutting continues to be one of the chief rationales</b> in recent deals,â Mr. Sorkin writes. â âSynergy,â an overused word in deal-making, has returned as âsavings.â â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Companies may also be turning to acquisitions to push up stock prices as <b> share buybacks become too expensive</b>, Mr. Sorkin writes. In a note to clients, David J. Kostin, the chief United States equity strategist at Goldman Sachs, recommended that companies focus on acquisitions rather than repurchasing shares while price-earnings ratios are so high. In recent years investors have generally rewarded companies that make big acquisitions by pushing up their share prices, Citigroup said, but Mr. Sorkin warns that the recent enthusiasm for mergers shouldnât be mistaken for a vote of confidence in the economy.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> <b> Netflix and General Motors</b> hold their annual meetings. MSCI will announce after 5 p.m. whether it will <b>add mainland Chinese stocks to its benchmark emerging market index</b>. <b> Jack Ma</b>, Alibabaâs founder, speaks at the Economic Club of New York at 11:45 a.m. <b>Ronald J. Kruszewski</b>, Stifel Financial Corporationâs chairman and chief executive, will be on Bloomberg Television at 9 a.m. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>CALPERS AIMS TO REDUCE MONEY MANAGER FEES</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The California Public Employeesâ Retirement System, the countryâs biggest state pension fund, has decided to reduce the amount it pays in asset management fees by cutting ties with half of the external investment managers of its funds, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/09/business/dealbook/calpers-to-cut-ties-with-many-fund-managers-to-save-on-fees.html"> Alexandra Stevenson reports in DealBook</a>. Calpers will inform its investment board this month about its plans to reduce the number of external managers to <b>100 from 212</b>. As part of that move, Calpers will <b>cut the number of private equity firms it uses to 30 from 98</b>, giving the remaining managers $30 billion to oversee. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As it anticipates a shortfall between payments to retirees and contributions from active workers, Calpers has been working to simplify its portfolio and increase returns by reducing the fees paid to outside money managers. Last year, it paid <b>$1.6 billion in management fees</b>, $400 million of which was a one-time payment for its real estate managers, a Calpers spokesman said. Pension funds across the country, which are facing the same financial pressures, are also taking a hard look at fees, especially as <b>returns by external money managers have been disappointing</b> in recent years.<br />
</p>
</div>
